revision.text:
'''Rental income''' is taxed under [[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 15 of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988|Schedule A]], if it arises from UK land<ref>[[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 15 of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988|Section 15 of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988]]</ref>, and under Case V of [[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 18 of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988|Schedule D]] if it arises from overseas land<ref>[[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 18 of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988|Section 18 of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988]].</ref>. The rules for UK and overseas land are the same<ref>[[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 70A of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988|Section 70A of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988]]</ref>.

In most instances a company is deemed to have a single Schedule A business. If, however, it is a partner in a partnership, rental income from that partnership is deemed to be a separate Schedule A business.<ref>[[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 15 of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988|Section 15 of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988]].</ref> These rules are amended for life assurance companies.<ref>A life assurance company, by virtue of [[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 432AA of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988|section 432AA of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988]] is deemed to have the following categories of business (for accounting periods beginning on or after 1 January 2007:

*solely linked basic life assurance and general annuity business;
*business linked to pension, child trust fund and/or individual savings account business;
*solely linked non-life long-term business;
*non-linked long-term business;
*business outside the long-term insurance fund.

Additionally, UK land linked to overseas life assurance business is treated as a separate Schedule A business by virtue of [[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 441B of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988|section 441B of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988]]</ref>

Rental income is calculated in the same way as trading income<ref>Sections [[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 21A of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988|21A]] and [[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 21B of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988|21B]] of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988.</ref>. In practice this means identifying the part of the profit shown in the financial statements that relates to rental income and making certain adjustments<ref>[[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 42 of the Finance Act 1998|Section 42 of the Finance Act 1998]].</ref> There are, however, some special rules that apply to taxing rental income that do not apply to trading income.

These are:

*A Schedule A charge can arise on mutual business<ref>[[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 21C of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988|Section 21C of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988]]</ref>;
*There are special rules dealing with [[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Corporation tax/Leases|leases]];
*There are special rules dealing with [[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Corporation tax/Furnished holiday accommodation|furnished holiday accommodation]];
*There is a special rule allowing a deduction for expenditure on sea walls<ref>[[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 30 of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988|Section 30 of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988]]</ref>.

